msDesc.head: Dictes and Sayings of the Philosophers

msItem.title: Prologue to the Dictes and Sayings of the Philosophers [English translation of French translation of the Arabic Kitāb mukhtār al-ḥikam wa-maḥāsin al-kalim by Guillaume de Tignonville]
msItem.author: Anthony Woodville, Earl Rivers
msItem.incipit: 1r Where it is so that euery humayn Creature by the suffraunce of our lord god is born and ordeigned to be subgette and thral vnto the stormes of fortune / And so in diuerse and many sondry wyses man is perplexid with worldly aduersitees / Of the whiche I Antoine Wydeuille Erle Ryuyeres lord Scales etcaetera haue largely and in many different maners haue had my parte
msItem.explicit: 3r But allegge the deffaulte to myn vncomyng with the dyuersytees of the bookes humbly desyryng the reformacioun therof with myn excuse and the rather syn after my rudenes not expert I in my maner folowed my copye and the ground I had to speke vpon as here after ensiewis

msItem.title: Dictes and Sayings of the Philosophers [English translation of French version of the Arabic Kitāb mukhtār al-ḥikam wa-maḥāsin al-kalim by Guillaume de Tignonville]
msItem.author: Abu al-Wafa' al-Mubashshir ibn Fatik (author)
Anthony Woodville, Earl Rivers (translator)
msItem.incipit: 4r Sedechias was the first Philosophir by whoom through the wil and pleaser of oure lorde god Sapience was vnderstande and lawes resceyued . Whiche Sedechias saide that euery creature of good beleue ought to haue in hym sixtene vertues
msItem.explicit: 73v And it was axid of him what is the signe of litil forsight and litil knowlege / he ansuerd one to yeue trust wher he hath ben deceyued / And suffise you with the translacion of the sayinges of these philosopheres.

msItem.title: Chapter about the sayings of Socrates on women added to the Dictes and Sayings of the Philosophers [English translation of French version of the Arabic Kitāb mukhtār al-ḥikam wa-maḥāsin al-kalim by Guillaume de Tignonville]
msItem.author: William Caxton
msItem.incipit: 74r Here endeth the book named the dictes or sayengis of the philosophhres [sic] enprynted by me William Caxton at Westmestre the yere of our lord .M. CCCC. lxxvij. Whiche book is late translated out of frenshe into englyssh . by the Noble and puissant lord Lord Antone Erle of Ryuyers lord of Scales and of the Ile of Wyght / Defendour and directour of the siege apostolique / for our holy fader the Pope in this Royame of Englond and Gouernour of my lord Prynce of Wales
msItem.explicit: 76r And a woman sayde to hym . wylt thou haue ony othe . woman than me And he ansuerde to her Arte not thou ashamed toffre thyself to hym . that demandeth ner desireth the not

msItem.title: Epilogue to the to the Dictes and Sayings of the Philosophers [English translation of French version of the Arabic Kitāb mukhtār al-ḥikam wa-maḥāsin al-kalim by Guillaume de Tignonville]
msItem.author: William Caxton
msItem.incipit: 76r-76v Lo these ben the dictes and sayengis of the phylosophre Socrates whiche he wrote in his book / And certaynly he wrote no worse than afore is rehersed And for asmoche as it is acordaunt . that his dyctes and sayengis shold be had as wel as others therfore I haue sette it in thende of this booke . And also somme persones per auenture that haue red this booke in frensshe wold haue arette a grette defaulte in me that I had not do my deuoir in visiting and ouerseeyng of my lordes book acording to his desir / And somme other also happely might haue supposed that Socrates had wreton moche more ylle of women than here afore is specified / wherfore in satisfyeng of all parties and also for excuse of the saide socrates I haue sette these saide dyctes and sayengis a parte in thende of this book / to thentent that yf my sayd lord or ony other persone what someuer he or she be that shal rede or here it / that If they be not wel plesyd wyth all that they wyth a penne race it out or ellys rente the leef out of the booke / Humbly requyryng and besechyng my sayd lord to take no displaysir on me so presumyng but to pardone where as he shal fynde faulte / and that it plese hym to take the labour of thenpryntyng in gre [sic] and thanke / whiche gladly haue done my dyligence in thaccomplyssyng of his desire and commandement / In whyche I am bounden so to do for the good reward that I haue resseyuyd of his sayd lordship / Whom I beseche Almyghty god tencrece and to contynue in his vertuous disposicion in this world / And after thys lyf to lyue euerlastyngly in heuen Amen

msItem.title: Medical recipe
msItem.incipit: 76v Take Isope an hanful red fenell nettyll cropes of ech half an hanfull elanacampana rotte halfe an aunce genger anised fenell sed of ech half an ounce barly an hanfull lycores in stobes brosyd ij ownce feges xij cut pesfyl boll all þet in a galon of cler rennynge water tyll þe water be consumed to halffe then strene it thro with a cloth and drynk it loke water evyn and morne as long as it lastys

listBibl.bibl: Mooney (1995), p. 151 [offers another transcription that differs from the transcription in this record]

msItem.title: A lover's complaint
msItem.incipit: 77r Alass to chom schall I complane / of this grett payn þat I In dur / ffor dred of danger and dyssdan
msItem.explicit: 77r I [crossed out: Re] commend me to yov a boff all thyng / be schesch yov to gav me In Rememerauns / And I schall pray to þe hevyn kyng to hav yov in his governauns
msItem.note: All the poems ff. 77r-77v have been added by the same hand.

msItem.title: Female revoiced version of Chaucer's 'Against women unconstant'
msItem.incipit: 77r Yong man for yovr nowfangellnys / many [crossed out: this] is the lady þat hass povt yov owt of her gras
msItem.explicit: 77r [crossed out: lyg] lyȝght fore somer ye wot what I mene / In stad of blov ye may wer gren
msItem.note: Possibly revoiced by a woman author [see Mooney (2000), passim].
Below, the poem's final words are repeated: of blov ye may were gren.
All the poems ff. 77r-77v have been added by the same hand.

msItem.title: 'Manerly Margery Mylk and ale' (an amorous flyting)
msItem.author: John Skelton
msItem.incipit: 77v A I be shrew yow be ma my fay / This wantoun clarkes be nyce all wayt
msItem.explicit: 77v yett for his love þat all has wroght / wed me ore elles I dy for thought / gvpp crischen clovt your breth is staill / go manerly margerie melke and aill
msItem.note: All the poems ff. 77r-77v have been added by the same hand.

supportDesc.support: Paper, folded in folio. Folios 1r: Bull's head with a five-petalled flower.

foliation.note: Numbering in pencil in the upper right-hand corner of the rectos.

Four loose papers with correspondence about the incunable's watermarks are kept with the book, between the front cover and the first flyleaf. For the purpose of reference in this electronic catalogue record, these papers have been allocated the following names: [Correspondence 1], [Correspondence 2], and [Watermarks].

collation.p:
Quire dj is out of order as follows: 1-2, 4, 3, 6, 5, 7-8. This has been indicated by a modern hand with pencil numbers in the upper margins of ff. 27r-30r: 2, 1, 4, 3.
Quire a8 (ff. 1-8)
Quire b8 (ff. 9-16)
Quire cj8 (ff. 17-24)
Quire dj8 (ff. 25-32)
Quire ej8 (ff. 33-40)
Quire fj8 (ff. 41-48)
Quire gj8 (ff. 49-56)
Quire hj8 (ff. 57-64)
Quire ij8 (ff. 65-72)
Quire kj6-1 (ff. 73-77: ?6th leaf missing)

layout.seg: Ruled in ink, frame and line ruling. Single columns. 29 lines to the page, printed below top line.

handNote.p: Handwritten added medical recipe by a single hand on f. 76 in a cursive secretary script with anglicana features.
Handwritten added poems by a single hand on ff. 77r-77v in a cursive secretary script with anglicana features.

decoNote.p: One large (4-line) blue and red initial inside a frame or red and brown penwork and pen-flourishing in the same colours extending into the inner margin on f. 4r.
Large (3-line) plain initials in blue or red painted over printed guide letters in blank spaces throughout the manuscript.
Paraphs in blue or red ink (alternating pattern).

note.p: Quire numbers a-b, and aj-kj written in pencil by a modern hand in the lower outer corners of the rectos of first leaves of quires, and crosses on lower outer corners of the rectos of the innermost leaves of quires.

[1] An (?) 18th-century title inscription on f. [ii] recto: The Sayings of the Philosophers translated out of Latin into French by Messire Jehan de Teonville Provost of Parys (vide Pref:) and from thence into English by Antonie Earl of Ryvyers, lord of Scales printed by William Caxton at Westminster A:D: 1477.

[2] Marginal annotations by a late 15th- or early 16th-century hand: this hathe withdravyn my hart from hunting (f. 5r); novght (f. 24r); stopping his (f. 30r); a trov frend (f. 30v); inconveniable [replacing printed: couenable] (f. 45r); And it hauyt and Nycomake sayd [copying the final printed line on the page] (f. 65v); dictes and sayengis of the phylosophre [copying title on page] (f. 76r).
A late 15th- or early 16th-century hand has added Nota in margins throughout.
A late 15th- or early 16th-century hand has added prices (account notes) on ff. 1v, 3r, and 75v-76r.

binding.p: English panel-style binding from the late 17th or first half of the 18th century with an outer panel of double and an middle panel triple blind-tooled fillets with fleurons at its corners, and an inner panel made with blind stamps; the spine with 5 raised bands and a gold-tooled red leather label with the gold-stamped title: Wm Caxton Dicts - Philos - 1477.
Binding height: 285 mm; width: 205 mm; depth: 30 mm.

note.p: [3] Modern loose papers kept with the manuscript: [a] Printed correspondence between Paul Needham and Dr Philip Gaskell, Librarian of Trinity College, July 1979, concerning this incunable's watermarks ([Correspondence 1], and [Correspondence 2]). It is accompanied by two small sheets of paper with tracings of a scissors watermark made with the aid of transmitted light ([Watermarks]).

provenance.p: [?]Antony: a man of this name may have owned or accessed the manuscript: the word Atone that was aded to the upper margin of f. 12r in a late 15th- or early 16th-century hand may be a name inscription.

[?]Margery: a woman of this name may have owned or accessed the manuscript: the word Margere that was aded to the outer margin of f. 28r in a late 15th- or early 16th-century hand may be a name inscription. This previously unnoticed inscription may be of particular interest for the unique copy of a female-voiced version of Chaucer's Against Women Unconstant on f. 77r: as Mooney (2000) argues, the revision was probably made by a woman author. Although the hands of the (possible) name inscription and the poem seem to be different, it may indicate a particular circulation of this incunable among a female audience.

history.acquisition: Acquired by Trinity College from an unknown source and at an unknown time but probably before 1760 as is suggested by the presence of of a printed ex libris engraved by William Stephens, fl. c. 1740-c. 1760 (W. Stephens sculp), featuring the College's heraldic coat of arms, motto (Virtus Vera Nobilitas), and name (Coll: Trin: Cant:), on f. [ii] recto. The college's current classmark VI.18.2 printed on paper labels pasted onto the spine and written in pencil on the inside of the front cover; and its (?) 19th-century book stamp on ff. 2r, 76v, 77v.

recordHist.source: This catalogue entry draws on Linne R. Mooney, Manuscripts in the Library of Trinity College, Cambridge, The Index of Middle English Prose, Handlist XI (Woodbridge: Brewer, 1995), p. 151; and The Digital Index of Middle English Verse.
